english:
  title: Record of the Miraculous Manifestations of the Sixteen-Foot Golden Image of Wangnyun Temple
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Consider how the Buddha's teaching spread to the Three Kingdoms, reaching from the center to the furthest corners, with temples appearing as far as the eye could see. Scarcely a temple exists without its sacred image. Yet all Buddhas are one body. Among the places where Buddha images are enshrined, some display miraculous manifestations while others do not. This lies beyond the comprehension of ordinary minds—how could we presume to measure it? And yet, the supernatural powers and skillful means of the Buddhas and Bodhisattvas move freely without constraint, neither possible nor impossible. Such things cannot be sought through form and appearance alone. If miracles do not manifest, it is not that they cannot—merely that their workings are veiled for a time. When circumstances align and sentient beings are receptive, the miraculous reveals itself. This too is the natural unfolding of compassionate means, reaching even into the minutest affairs of the worthy. Through ordinary human eyes, how could one fail to be astonished and moved to deepen one's faith? When sincere devotion becomes steadfast, the Buddha responds at once, and the miracles grow ever more apparent. This is why the world speaks of certain temples and certain images possessing great spiritual power.

    North of the capital stands a temple called Wangnyun, a great sanctuary where the dharma wheel turns eternally. Within it resides a golden image of Vairocana Buddha, sixteen feet tall. It is said that long ago, two monks named Gubin and Gyeokwang made a vow to cast this golden image. They became what is called in common speech the "pillars"—those who inspire the faithful to give alms and support the Buddha's work. Gubin oversaw the project while Gyeokwang assisted him. One day Gubin suddenly said to his companion: "Many things do not proceed as I wish, and my years grow long. I cannot see this through to completion. I must enter the Mountain of Bones and immolate myself. Do you gather my relics and carry them forth. With them you shall encourage the people to give, and none will refuse. Only then can this work be accomplished."

    Having spoken, he entered the mountain to cultivate the Way. On the fifteenth day of the eighth month of the year Bingsin, in a northern grotto of the great meditation hall, he set his body aflame while living. The venerable Gyeokwang collected the relics, placed them in a shrine, and carried them on his own back to the capital. As he went about seeking alms, from the highest officials to the common people, none refused to give. Treasures accumulated like mountains.

    Among the scattered officials in the district of boards, there lived a general in poverty who could offer no material gifts. He had a daughter of thirteen years, whom he offered in service. The venerable Gyeokwang reluctantly accepted her. A certain general in the southern quarter, though advanced in years and childless, ransomed the girl to be his adopted daughter, offering five hundred bolts of silk. A widow in Star Tower district, poor and having nothing precious to give, offered a great mirror that had long been lent to another. She said: "This mirror has been in another's keeping so long that I cannot yet reclaim it. But when the metal is cast, I shall surely bring it then." The venerable Gyeokwang agreed.

    When the time came to cast the metal, years had passed and he forgot. He poured the bronze without returning to collect the mirror. When the image was completed, every feature was perfectly formed and dignified—save for a flaw in the chest. The monks were greatly troubled and considered recasting. But the mirror's owner, hearing the image was done, came sorrowful yet resigned. She brought her mirror and placed it in the hollow. The flaw and the mirror fit together perfectly. Intending to seal it later with inscription, they waited until dawn. But when morning came, the mirror had fused of itself as if cast with the bronze, leaving not a trace. The people of the capital came to see in throngs, all marveling. This was the first miracle.

    When the image was complete, they wished to enshrine it in the golden hall that very day, but the door was too low. They planned to remove the lintel the next morning. When dawn came, the Buddha sat serenely in place as if by its own power. This was the second miracle.

    The Minister Choe Jeong-an held the sixteen-foot golden image in deep reverence. Since his residence bordered the temple to the south, each time he went to office he would descend from his horse at the temple gate, bow before the image, and proceed. Upon leaving office, he would dismount at the gate of the dynasty, bow twice, and walk past the temple gates before remounting. Whatever new thing he obtained, he would first offer it before tasting it himself. Often he would go to the hall and personally brew tea in offering. This continued for a long time until one night he dreamed the golden Buddha spoke: "Your service to me is sincere and diligent. Yet it does not equal the devotion of an old soldier who dwells to the south of the temple." The next day, the minister sent someone to find this man, and there was indeed an elderly soldier living there. The minister visited him and asked: "I have heard you hold in reverence the golden Buddha image. Is this true? How do you show your reverence?" The old soldier replied: "I have been paralyzed by wind-stroke these seven years. Each dawn and dusk when I hear the bell, I join my palms toward that place. What else can I do?" The minister said: "Then my own service to the Buddha is not as sincere as yours." From that day, he held the man in highest regard, giving him one measure of grain from each stipend. This was the third miracle.

    When the minister received his stipend one day, a monk in dark robes came to his gate begging food. The minister gave him rice. Watching him eat, the monk seemed extraordinary. The minister had another measure of rice specially prepared, which the monk consumed entirely without leaving a grain. Astonished, the minister gave him one measure of his stipend and sent a slave to carry it, following behind. At the gate, the monk insisted the slave return home, and carried the grain away himself. When the minister heard this, he sent men to search but found no trace. He went himself to follow, but heard only that a monk bearing rice had entered Wangnyun Temple. He went to the temple and searched but could not find him. By chance he decided to bow before the golden Buddha in the golden hall. There on the altar he found one measure of grain. Then he understood—the monk had been the Buddha's manifestation. This was the fourth miracle.

    All these tales were transmitted by the venerable Head Monk Gyeol to the great teacher Jeongrim of the dharma lineage. Jeongrim later became a Buddhist official, both being learned masters of profound faith. Would they have transmitted falsehoods? From the ancient accounts still spoken among the people: when the golden image was being brought to the temple, it was loaded on a great cart pulled by nearly a million people. The road was thronged. Even merchant-vendors of pork felt inspired to help push the cart. Yet suddenly it would not move. The monk in charge was puzzled and climbed high ground to observe. He saw a herd of pigs blocking the wheels. Understanding this was karmic obstruction, he forbade those people from pushing. Then the cart moved freely. This was the fifth miracle.

    From what people of both ancient and modern times have witnessed: when calamity is about to strike the realm, the golden image first sweats. Not only the image itself but the clay Bodhisattva attendants beside it and all characters in the stone-carved Flower Garland Sutra—whenever they are the names of Tathagata, Buddha, or Bodhisattva—become wet. All other characters remain dry. Thus does the golden image protect our nation, warning us beforehand. This was the sixth miracle.

    The venerable Gyeokwang began casting this image in the eighth year of King Seongjong, in the year Muja, the first year of the Song dynasty's Duangong era. It was completed ten years later in the year Dingyu. According to the account of Venerable Gyeol, the temple once suffered fire. All records and more than ten accounts of the image's miracles were lost in the flames. What this humble monk has transmitted is but what remained. Thus the miracles are not limited to these. Should later records of the lost accounts be discovered, they may be appended here.

    Regarding the minister's feeding of monks, accounts differ. Venerable Gyeol says a dark-robed monk came begging at the gate. But the elder practitioners now say this: The minister had daily alms given to one monk, instructing his slave: "Go seek out a monk. The first you meet shall be one of karmic connection—bring that one especially." One day as the slave searched, he encountered a monk in tattered robes, grotesquely ugly. The slave avoided him and sought another. Yet that same monk appeared again. This happened four times, but the slave, disgusted, refused to invite him and returned to report. The minister grew angry: "That is precisely the one of whom I spoke! Go at once and bring him!" The slave hurried out and finding the monk again, brought him to the house where the minister gave him food. Which account is true remains uncertain. Both have elements of wonder, so I have recorded both.

    The realm has ordered repairs to the deteriorating shrine of the golden image. The current Prime Minister from Cheongha, Minister Choe, has been greatly instrumental. He further heard that the Buddha canopies and dharma banners had decayed, and sighed, saying: "These are the very countenance of Buddhist ritual. Without splendid adornment, one cannot fulfill the greatest requirements of ceremony." He commanded artisans to construct them, and they blazed with jeweled light so dazzling that none had seen their like before. The minister reviewed the remaining records of the image's miracles and could not cease marveling. Yet seeing these were recorded in common speech and vernacular language, fearing they would not endure transmission, he commanded me to write them in proper form. This humble student dares to bow low and offer this record, adding a hymn in praise:

    One pure and luminous body—
    the moon reflected on autumn water.
    Draw near, and it shines brilliantly;
    reach to grasp it, and it recedes into distance.
    Vairocana's realm transcends
    all thought and discourse from their very origin.
    The maker of this image dreamed;
    the one who praises it dreams as well.
